Maria is playing bocce ball with her friend Ryan. She is trying to get her red ball closer to the yellow ball than Ryan's green ball is to the yellow ball. Her plan is to roll her ball into Ryan's to push it out of the way. The blue lines are vectors representing momentum of the bocce balls.

  • Drag the black point to change what Maria's ball's momentum will be after the collision.

SCI.BIO.322.1.title: DNA Fingerprinting
SCI.BIO.322.1.summary:
A crime has been committed at CK-12! Someone went into the kitchen and made an enormous mess while most of the office was in a meeting, leaving behind only a single strand of hair as evidence. The team at CK-12 have decided to find the culprit using science!

Only two people could have committed the crime, Carl or Paul, as everyone else was together in a meeting at the time. Carl and Paul do not get along well so no-one believes they committed the crime together. To determine which of the two is the culprit the CK-12 team will use DNA fingerprinting.

DNA fingerprinting is carried out by isolating DNA from evidence (unknown samples) and suspects or persons of interest (known samples). These DNA are then treated with restriction enzymes that cut them at specific sequences and are then analyzed using an agarose gel to see how many times the enzymes cut each sample. If an enzyme cuts two samples an identical number of times in identical places, there is a very high chance the two samples came from the same person.

 

Here the DNA evidence and DNA samples from both Carl and Paul have been treated with restriction enzymes and are ready to be analyzed on a gel.

  • Drag the red point to the right to apply voltage to the gel and separate the DNA fragments!
  • Answer the questions that follow to analyze the gel and figure out who made a huge mess in the CK-12 kitchen!

MAT.CAL.247.title: Limits of Polynomial and Rational Functions
Evaluating Limits of Rational Functions
MAT.CAL.247.summary:
Do you remember how the rational functions in the form @$r(x)=\frac{1}{x-h}+k@$, where @$(h, k)@$ is the intersection of the vertical and horizontal asymptotes, are drawn? They are two graphs that are bounded by the vertical and horizontal asymptotes in opposite quadrants. How would you find the limits of these functions given certain types of @$x-@$values? 

  • Move the red point in order to interact with the asymptotes and change the values of @$h@$ and @$k@$  
  • Move the green dot in order to simulate @$x-@$values getting closer to a certain value [orange dot] 
  • Move the purple dot in order to change the value that the @$x-@$values approaches to.

SCI.BIO.338.6.title: DNA Fingerprinting
SCI.BIO.338.6.summary:
A crime has been committed at CK-12! Someone went into the kitchen and made an enormous mess while most of the office was in a meeting, leaving behind only a single strand of hair as evidence. The team at CK-12 have decided to find the culprit using science!

Only two people could have committed the crime, Carl or Paul, as everyone else was together in a meeting at the time. Carl and Paul do not get along well so no-one believes they committed the crime together. To determine which of the two is the culprit the CK-12 team will use DNA fingerprinting.

DNA fingerprinting is carried out by isolating DNA from evidence (unknown samples) and suspects or persons of interest (known samples). These DNA are then treated with restriction enzymes that cut them at specific sequences and are then analyzed using an agarose gel to see how many times the enzymes cut each sample. If an enzyme cuts two samples an identical number of times in identical places, there is a very high chance the two samples came from the same person.

 

Here the DNA evidence and DNA samples from both Carl and Paul have been treated with restriction enzymes and are ready to be analyzed on a gel.

  • Drag the red point to the right to apply voltage to the gel and separate the DNA fragments!
  • Answer the questions that follow to analyze the gel and figure out who made a huge mess in the CK-12 kitchen!
